titlestmt.titleproper: Guide to the John Vliet Lindsay Papers
titlestmt.author: by Jane Thompson, Sheila Conneen, Linda Billingsley, John Dojka, and staff of Manuscripts and Archives

publicationstmt.publisher: Yale University. Department of Manuscripts and Archives

profiledesc.creation: This finding aid was produced using ArchivesSpace on Tuesday April 23, 2019 at 07:15

repository.corpname: Yale University. Department of Manuscripts and Archives

did.abstract: The papers, divided into two parts, document the life and political career of John Lindsay from student days at Yale University through his two terms as mayor of New York City, 1965-1973. Part I. contains pre-congressional and congressional papers covering the years 1944-1965 and includes his Yale senior thesis, personal correspondence and subject files, campaign records, and congressional papers for the years 1959-1965. Part II. contains Lindsay's personal mayoral papers covering the years 1965-1973. The papers include personal correspondence, schedules, appointment books, subject files, campaign records, the papers of ten assistants to the mayor, photographs and other materials. Accessions to the collection provide additional material relating to Lindsay's congressional and mayoral years, as well as his 1972 Democratic presidential nomination bid and his 1980 Senate primary campaign.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Original audiovisual materials, as well as preservation and duplicating masters, may not be played. Researchers must consult use copies, or if none exists pay for a use copy, which is retained by the repository. Researchers wishing to obtain an additional copy for their personal use should consult Copying Services information on the Manuscripts and Archives web site.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Copyright has been transferred to Yale University for unpublished materials authored or otherwise produced by John Vliet Lindsay. Copyright has been transferred by Anne Phipps Sidamon-Eristoff to Yale University for unpublished materials authored or otherwise produced by Constantine Sidamon-Eristoff in Accession 2014-M-053. Copyright to the unpublished writings of James Carberry in Accession 2007-M-061 is retained by Ava Carberry until March 13, 2017. Copyright status for other collection materials is unknown. Transmission or reproduction of materials protected by U.S. Copyright Law (Title 17, U.S.C.) beyond that allowed by fair use requires the written permission of the copyright owners. Works not in the public domain cannot be commercially exploited without permission of the copyright owners. Responsibility for any use rests exclusively with the user.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged in two parts, oversize material, and seven additions: Part I. Pre-Congressional and Congressional Papers. Part II. New York City Mayoral Personal Papers.

Part I is organized into fourteen series: I. Yale College, 1944. II. Executive assistant to the U.S. Attorney General, 1954-1958. III. American Bar Association, 1950-1960. Personal correspondence, 1949-1961. V. Campaign records, 1958. VI. Appointment books, 1959-1965. VII. Bills introduced, 1959-1965. VIII. NATO Parliamentarian's Conference and Ditchley Foundation conference records, 1955-1965. IX. Policy file, chronological, 1958-1965. X. Policy file, by subject, 1958-1965. XI. Speech file, 1958-1965. XII. Constituent newsletters and questionnaires, 1959-1965. XIII. Publication reprints, 1959-1965. XIV. Biographical newspaper and magazine articles, 1959-1965.

Part II is organized into twenty-five series: I. Personal correspondence, 1966-1973. II. Schedules and fact sheets, 1965-1973. III. Appointment books and journals, 1965-1973. IV. Daily crisis calendars, 1970-1973. V. Speech files, 1966-1969. VI. Campaign records, 1965. VII. Campaign records, 1969. VIII. Presidential campaign, 1972. IX. National Advisory Commission on Civil Disorders, 1968. X. Project management staff, 1972-1973. XI. Robert W. Sweet (Deputy Mayor), 1969. XII. Richard R. Aurelio (Deputy Mayor), 1969-1972. XIII. Edward Hamilton (Deputy Mayor), 1969-1973. XIV. Sid Davidoff (Assistant to the Mayor), 1965-1973. XV. Nathan Leventhal (Assistant to the Mayor), 1970-1972. XVI. Jay Kriegel (Assistant to the Mayor), 1966-1973. XVII. Constantine Sidamon-Eristoff (Assistant to the Mayor), 1966. XVIII. Steven Isenberg (Assistant to the Mayor), 1970-1973. XIX. Richard Weston (Assistant to the Mayor), 1972-1973. XX. Peter Goldmark (Assistant to the Mayor), 1965-1970. XXI. Photographs, 1950-1972. XXII. Audio material, 1965-1972. XXIII. Telephone conversation records: lists and memoranda, 1968-1973. XXIV. Campaign workers and fund raising records, 1958-1973. XXV. Restricted personal financial records, 1957-1971.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The papers, divided into two parts, document the life and political career of John Lindsay from student days at Yale University through his two terms as mayor of New York City, 1965-1973. Part I contains pre-congressional and congressional papers covering the years 1944-1965 and includes his Yale senior thesis, personal correspondence and subject files, campaign records, and congressional papers for the years 1959-1965. Part II contains Lindsay's personal mayoral papers covering the years 1965-1973. The papers include personal correspondence, schedules, appointment books, subject files, campaign records, the papers of ten assistants to the mayor, photographs and other materials. Accessions to the collection provide additional material relating to Lindsay's mayoral years, as well as his 1972 Democratic presidential nomination bid and his 1980 Senate primary campaign.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: John V. Lindsay: born on November 24, 1921, in New York City; lawyer, former mayor of New York City; B.A., Yale, 1944, LL.B., Yale Law School, 1948; law practice in New York City, 1949- ; executive assistant to the United States Attorney General, 1955-1957; member of the United States House of Representatives, 86th-89th Congress, 17th District, New York, 1959-1965; Mayor of New York City, 1966-1973; vice chairman, National Commission on Civil Disorders, 1967. Died on December 19, 2000, in Hilton Head, South Carolina.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The materials in this accession were donated in 2014 by Mrs. Anne Phipps Sidamon-Eristoff, widow of Constantine Sidamon-Eristoff. Highly active in civic affairs and conservative political organizations, Constantine Sidamon-Eristoff became Congressman Lindsay's executive assistant in New York in March 1965, continued on as Lindsay's assistant during his subsequent mayoral run and administration, and was appointed by Lindsay as Commissioner of Highways in 1967 and Transportation Administrator in 1968.

Sidamon-Eristoff's papers document Lindsay's 1964 congressional and 1965 mayoral campaigns, as well as affairs of the Transportation Administration spanning 1967-1973. The bulk of the materials focus on Lindsay's 1965 mayoral run, including extensive documentation of campaign finances, internal memos and training materials for campaign workers, campaign operations and contact lists organized by election and assembly district, and campaign literature, press releases and position papers. Also included are Sidamon-Eristoff's notes, speeches, reports, correspondence, and personal and professional files from his years with the Lindsay administration.
